##In-depth report on a 30-hour journey home

Wechat Bqshenyidu

Features, Beijing Youth Daily, the official public number

Reporter / Tong Xiaoyu

Editor / Yang Baolu & Song Jianhua

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Service area personnel are disinfecting their cars

The license plate "a" has never been as conspicuous as it is today.

On Jan. 23, traffic in Wuhan was cut off because of pneumonia caused by COVID-19. The city's public transport is suspended, no special reasons for residents to leave Wuhan, the airport, the railway station is also temporarily closed. But many had left Wuhan before, crossing the bridge road back to their hometowns or visiting their long cherished destinations, only to find themselves caught off guard by a trial of isolation and acceptance.

The Changning Family and their friends were stuck in the middle of the moment: Before Zhong Nanshan announced the confirmation, they had safely driven away for a holiday; after the outbreak, they had to return to Wuhan. For 30 hours, she had to tell her children that they were afraid of the virus, not of them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After 30 hours of driving, I finally got back to Wuhan

The most special New Year's Eve

At around 5 pm on January 28, we got off the highway from Gongjialing, after a 30-hour journey, and finally returned to Wuhan, home.

It's probably the most special 30 hours of our lives.

On January 17, my family of three and my sister's family of three, as well as my sister's best friend, took our children, five adults and three children, from Wuhan to Baekdu Mountain. The three of US drove an SUV, three of us in turns. Two DADS and three kids driving a commercial vehicle. People want to go skiing in Baekdu Mountain, which they did last year, and eleven has booked a resort in Baekdu Mountain online.

Before we left, I saw some news on the Internet, saying that Wuhan had discovered a new type of pneumonia. There were quite a lot of patients in the hospital, but the news said that it could be prevented and controlled. Only a limited number of people passed from one person to another. People in the community did not seem nervous. Everything was as usual. We didn't expect it to be this bad, and we didn't get any notification of the outbreak, so we didn't even think to wear masks when we went out. Whether you are staying in a hotel in Shandong province, watching the Tianjin eye in Tianjin or visiting the Forbidden City in Shenyang, there is no problem. If you buy a ticket in Mukden Palace, you can buy it directly with your ID card. At that time, everything went as usual. There are more people in these places.

It was not until the 21st that news of the outbreak became serious. We were in Shenyang at the time, and when we heard the news, we rushed to buy masks, which were already hard to buy. We had to go to four pharmacies to get two packs of disposable masks.

We also watched academician Zhong Nanshan's speech, realized that the epidemic was quite serious, and worried about what others might think of US coming from Wuhan, we called the resort hotel in Baekdu Mountain in Shenyang and asked them, we are from Wuhan, can you check in normally? If not, we will stop at Shenyang and return to Wuhan. The hotel just rsvp'd yes. On the 21st, we successfully checked into a resort hotel in Baekdu Mountain.

At the hotel, we checked in with the staff. The hotel's service and emergency measures were good. We had our temperature taken on time. We stayed in a large suite with beds on both sides of a large living room in the middle. Eight people were basically in the same room. Chinese food was delivered directly to the room, we also went to the pharmacy to buy two thermometers, every day have nothing to do to take the temperature.

I booked three ski instructors, put down a deposit. But, for fear of causing unnecessary trouble, we took the initiative to communicate with the coach, saying that we are from Wuhan. If the coach mind, we won't go. At that time, there were two coaches who were afraid and didn't want to take us, we said we could stop skating if we wanted to, and there was only one coach left to take it. Then went to the infirmary to take the temperature, we are normal temperature, when in fact already felt that things are serious, the original people have so much care.

On the 22nd, we went skiing with the coach. I went back to my hotel to watch the news, and I kept getting messages on my phone about the outbreak, and some friends sent me messages to remind me that we really realized it was serious. Our coach was miserable, too. He went back in quarantine.

We immediately communicated with the hotel, asked for self-isolation, let them send food to the room, the ticket has also been postponed, scheduled for next year.

At this time, all kinds of news about the epidemic swept in, and the news that Wuhan had cut off foreign traffic came from Florida at that time. We never thought it could be so serious. I remember on the morning of the 23rd, the day before New Year's Eve, we were already preparing to be quarantined that day in our room, one got up and woke up to hear such news. For a while, everyone was pretty nervous. I felt that the epidemic was getting worse and worse. At that time, I was most worried about the old people in my family. The News said that the mortality rate was high among the old people. So I kept calling my family and telling them to wear masks and try not to go out.

Because did not see around the real case or critical situation, the family old man also has been skeptical. We need to make a video call every two or three hours, look around the house, and tell the old man. We are also afraid of the elderly did not eat, because on the 23rd, it is said that a lot of supermarkets in the day to buy, we told the elderly do not go. Fortunately, it was near the New Year, the family has a lot of things, at least two or three days is enough.

This is probably the most special New Year's Eve we've ever spent outside. When we came out from Wuhan, we brought some food, the hotel gave us Ginseng chicken soup, we made a hot pot, so we ate reunion dinner.

Go back, or stay

Then we had to face the question, should we go back or stay?

On the 26th, due to pneumonia, the scenic spot began to close policy. After all, we negotiated with the hotel. After all, it was too far to drive back. More than 2300 kilometers. The hotel also communicated with the local government, but the policy kept changing. At first, the hotel said it would accommodate US until the 29th, but after the 29th it was uncertain. We wanted to live until the 29th, so we contacted the next town, and we were looking for a place to be isolated, but the government responded that we could only be isolated.

On the 25th, government workers told us that there seemed to be a suspected case in the place where the quarantine was concentrated, which made it impossible for us to do so, and we were even more afraid to go there. We even called the police, who said it wasn't a police matter, it wasn't a dispute, and they couldn't arrange it.

Family and friends advised us to stay put and wait. After much deliberation, we were torn: Go back, Wuhan is in the midst of an outbreak, and the road to drive more than 20 hours, a breath back is very dangerous; do not go back, we take the children, outside do not know what will happen.

We collected all kinds of information about the epidemic and made many calls to friends from all walks of life. I wanted to go to Shenyang for a few days to see what was going on, and I had a long discussion about it, imagining all kinds of things that would happen, and making plans to deal with it. We talked about it until the middle of the night, and then we all agreed that we wanted the same thing, and we went back.

We had planned to spend the Spring Festival outside, only this time of the year there is a holiday, we would have been scheduled to return on the 28th, just on the sixth day, will start to work. But nothing has changed as fast as we planned.

On January 27, we got out of the hotel a little after 11:00 a.m. and went straight to the highway.

We did not dare to go to the supermarket supplies, worried that a supermarket will stop us, the parents of the stewed beef braised duck wing steamed, with the hotel sent a case of mineral water, 3 boxes of milk, a pile of bread, and so on in a hurry to start.

The night before we left, we found the SUV's tires were scratched and badly worn, so we contacted the mechanic, and our ski instructor helped us contact the mechanic. When the garage was closed for the new year, we went to the local people to help change the tire, but as soon as they heard that we were a's car, no one would help us. On the morning of the 27th, we decided we couldn't wait any longer, so the two dads had to do it themselves by reversing the front and back wheels of the SUV.

We needed two jacks to switch the front and back tires. We were short of one, so we borrowed it from another driver. Later, we borrowed it from a taxi driver. Worried that the taxi driver would mind that we were from Wuhan, we bought the Jacks for 300 yuan.

It wasn't until we got back to Wuhan that our two fathers told us that the car might not have been properly topped when we changed the tire.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I didn't even dare to roll down the window to refuel

To Be "the center of attention. "

Along the way, we learned what it means to focus on the object.

We all experienced SARS in 2003, so even if we had some troubles, we were in a relatively calm state. We added all kinds of wechat groups, and we know that e-a license plate stands out. When we parked downstairs, we could see the car from upstairs, sitting in a row by the window, looking down at what was going on or what was going on. Luckily, nothing happened during that time.

When we passed the first service area, there was a garage with the door open, so we went to get gas. In the process of filling gas, the garage staff saw the license plate, called the police to find the police.

The police came quickly. We registered our ID card and took our temperature. It was late at night and we wanted to take the kids to a restaurant for dinner. But the police suggested that we buy to eat, but in the north, so cold, buy things out of the cold can not eat, we also worry about the weather is too cold children catch a cold.

At 11 p.m. , we found a Ramen restaurant in a small service area. After a routine inspection, we went in and ate a mouthful of steaming beef noodles. Although there were only three slices of beef, we couldn't help but feel tears coming to our eyes, just like doing the wrong thing, secretly can not let others know that we are Wuhan people, the children are very sensible, do not speak, buried in eating.

On the way we added a few stranded in the Wuhan People's Home Group, we are quite miserable. We're in the group trying to help people. Whenever I see a group of people "said I arrived home, I arrived in Wuhan" , everyone will be very excited, is a kind of encouragement to each other.

About 12 o'clock in the evening, we are very sleepy, from Shandong to Tianjin Walk, the smog is particularly severe, the road is very dark, very difficult to go, we are very afraid. Walk to about two o'clock in the morning want to rest, found the service area, security came, we cooperate register, take temperature. We told the security guard to sleep in the car, take a rest, but at four o'clock, the staff came to wake us up, said the service area leader to check, if you see Wuhan will be more trouble, you quickly go.

We'll just wake up the kids, go to the bathroom, and get out of here.

On two or three occasions in the rest areas above the highway, staff members would speak very harshly and in a cross tone when they saw the license plate of the E A. We also thought, big New Year's Day, still have to do these jobs, must be very upset. So I think I can understand, adjust their own mentality, to tell people. The service area has any request, we all cooperate, actually after the communication, everybody manner relaxed.

In fact, before the return trip, there is no special feeling, just feel that the way back may be more difficult, the children on the road quite obedient, has been very cooperative, but can feel their fear. Along the way, we had to park far away from the service area and run to the bathroom so we wouldn't be allowed in for fear of being seen. At dinner, we would tell the children to eat quietly and eat quickly. We were worried that the children would come into contact with each other and infect each other. We were also worried that other people would know that we were from Wuhan and drive us away.

The children have asked, why he can not let others know that we are Wuhan people, why do they want to Wuhan people? I told them that our city was sick, that people would be a little scared, but they would help us. This is our home, and no matter what happens to her, we still love her, so we're going home.

When the child asked like this, I felt quite innocent and quite aggrieved. In fact, we should not be treated like this just because we are a license plate of Hubei. Cars with a license plate of Hubei are infected with virus, is it safe for another car to run on the road? Should not be used in this way to divide, just because we are Wuhan People's identity, be excluded, be discriminated against. It shouldn't be like this. We're fighting the virus together, not the Wuhan People.

But we don't talk to kids about discrimination or not, and for kids, I want them to see the good, and I have to tell them something positive, and that can be very hard on them. The kid asked, "we're not sick. Why can't we ski? "? Fortunately, there are two teachers, along the way to explain to the children why this happens, we self-isolation, do not go around, is for their own safety, is responsible for themselves, others and society.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the intersection of the freeway

The common enemy is the virus

At 9:40 am on the 28th, when we reached the first service area that day, the children shouted that they were hungry, so we went into the rest area to look for food. Children have to go to the toilet, halfway to the service area was a fierce uncle came back, especially loudly told us, "what? Do not go, stop! "

The child was taken aback.

In fact, we have prepared all the way, in each service area, if let us go to the bathroom we go, let us eat we eat, if not let us go, we hurry away, refueling is the same. But by this roar, we adults are scared, then some panic and fear, but also very distressed children.

We're going to talk to him, and I don't think you should show it, even if you're feeling it right now, because if you don't control it, it can lead to conflict. I think at this point in time, anger or grievance does not help, the most important thing is to solve the problem, a smooth return home. After we talked it over with him, they didn't say anything, so he asked us to sign in, and then he let us in for breakfast.

When refueling, because saw our license plate, the staff did not even let us open the window, let us get off the car. He filled up the tank, put the Qr Code on the glass when he paid for it, swept it, and there was no communication.

I'm in the pharmaceutical industry, I deal with doctors a lot, and we also pay attention during the whole return journey. Many people may not know much about this disease or the process of prevention, and there will be some panic at some point, but the scary thing is that they just reject you and don't do anything to protect themselves.

We also made other preparations, in advance contact friends in Liaoning ready to live, but finally decided to drive back to Wuhan. We made it all the way from Baekdu Mountain to Wuhan without getting off because once we got off the highway we were in trouble and afraid of being stopped.

Back in Wuhan, after getting off the highway, a police car asked all the vehicles to register there, take temperature, they told us not to panic, but also told us to find a community if we have any difficulties in life.

As soon as we got into town, all three of our moms got all emotional and cried a lot. There was also tension and fear along the way. Everyone had been prepared psychologically for all sorts of things to happen. At times, it was quite sad. But none of us dared to release such feelings on the way, for fear that they would affect others, so there was a lot of positive energy, a lot of encouragement and a lot of fun.

The kids were so happy when they got off the bus, they jumped up. Before we broke up, we took some pictures of our three children, and then we sent each of them home, one by one, to say goodbye. We hugged as we parted, as if we had just been through life and death together.

These days, we have learned to joke, saying that Wuhan people are famous now, the license plate of Hubei a is known to the whole country, every time I see these, I feel very sad, we are the common enemy is the virus, not each other.

In order to protect personal privacy, Chang Ning is a pseudonym
